<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# Module Experiment 2 — Disk Scheduling Algorithms (SSTF, LOOK, C-SCAN)

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Disk Scheduling** is a fundamental Operating System subsystem that determines the **order in which pending I/O requests to the disk** are serviced by the disk arm. The primary objective is to **minimise the total seek time** (and therefore the total head movement) by intelligently reordering the queue of cylinder requests, thereby reducing the average response time and increasing the throughput of the disk subsystem.

In the **KTU 2024 Scheme Lab (PCCSL407)**, this experiment requires the student to:

1. Model a disk with **5,000 cylinders numbered 0 to 4,999**.
2. Generate a **random series of 10 cylinder requests** in that range.
3. Accept the **initial position of the disk head** as a **command-line argument**.
4. Implement and execute three algorithms — **SSTF**, **LOOK**, and **C-SCAN** — and report the **total head movements** (in cylinders) for each.

> [!NOTE]
> The cylinder count of **5,000** and request count of **10** are **fixed experimental parameters** mandated by the KTU lab manual. Do **not** deviate from these values during your viva or record submission.

The three algorithms under study belong to different scheduling families:

| Algorithm | Family | Selection Criterion |
|---|---|---|
| **SSTF** (Shortest Seek Time First) | Greedy / Distance-based | Pick request with **shortest absolute distance** from current head. |
| **LOOK** | Elevator (variant) | Move head in one direction servicing all requests, then **reverse** (no wrap-around to disk end). |
| **C-SCAN** (Circular SCAN) | Circular / One-way | Move in one direction to the disk end, **jump to 0**, then continue servicing. |

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — "The Library Librarian"

Imagine you are a **librarian in a 5,000-shelf library** (shelves numbered 0 to 4,999). Ten readers simultaneously request books from different shelves. You are currently standing at **shelf 2,150**. You have three strategies:

- 🧠 **SSTF (Shortest-Seek-Time First) — "Walk to the Nearest Reader"**: Regardless of direction, you always walk to the **closest reader** who is still waiting. This is greedy and feels natural, but a steady stream of new readers on the side you're already on could **starve** readers on the far side.

- 🛗 **LOOK — "The Building Elevator Algorithm"**: You decide to walk to the **highest-numbered request first**, picking up readers along the way. When there is no one left in the upward direction, you **turn around** and walk downward, picking up the rest. You don't go all the way to shelf 4,999 — you stop at the **last request in that direction** (that's why it's called "LOOK" — you only look as far as needed).

- 🔄 **C-SCAN — "The One-Way Conveyor Belt"**: You walk monotonically towards **higher-numbered shelves** until you reach the **end of the library (4,999)**. Then you **teleport back to shelf 0** and start servicing readers there. This guarantees a **uniform wait time** for all readers, which is fairer in real-time systems.

> [!TIP]
> **Intuition in one line**: SSTF = *nearest neighbour*, LOOK = *elevator with reversal at last request*, C-SCAN = *circular one-way sweep*.

---

## 1.3 Performance Metrics to Be Reported

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The program must report, for **each** of the three algorithms, the value:
> $$\text{Total Head Movement} = \sum_{i=1}^{n-1} \vert H_{i+1} - H_i \vert$$
> where $H_i$ is the cylinder number of the $i^{th}$ serviced request and $H_1$ is the **initial head position** (command-line argument). For C-SCAN, the wrap-around jump from cylinder 4,999 to 0 must **also be counted** in the total.

All metrics are measured in **number of cylinders traversed**. The algorithm with the **lowest** total head movement is considered the most efficient *for that particular request sequence*.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Algorithm 1 — SSTF (Shortest Seek Time First)

### Operating Principle
SSTF is a **greedy, distance-minimising** algorithm. At every step, the disk controller selects the pending request whose cylinder number is **closest to the current head position** (i.e., minimum absolute difference).

### Why It Works
- The **seek time** of a disk arm is approximately **proportional to the distance** the head must travel.
- Minimising the distance for **every individual move** tends to minimise the **total cumulative distance** (greedy heuristic).

### Why It Can Fail
- It can cause **starvation**: if new requests continuously arrive near the head, requests far away may wait indefinitely.
- It is **not fair** in the temporal sense — the worst-case response time is unbounded.

### Step-by-Step Operational Logic
1. Receive a queue of $n$ pending requests $R = \{r_1, r_2, \dots, r_n\}$.
2. Set `current_head = initial_position` (from command line).
3. Repeat $n$ times:
   - Find index $k$ such that $\vert r_k - \text{current\_head} \vert$ is **minimum** among all un-serviced requests.
   - Add $\vert r_k - \text{current\_head} \vert$ to total head movement.
   - Set `current_head = r_k`.
   - Mark request $r_k$ as serviced.

---

## 2.2 Algorithm 2 — LOOK

### Operating Principle
LOOK is the **practical variant of SCAN**. The head moves in one direction (say, increasing cylinder numbers), servicing every request it encounters, until it reaches the **last pending request in that direction**. It then **reverses direction** and services the rest.

### The Crucial Distinction: LOOK vs. SCAN
| Property | SCAN | LOOK |
|---|---|---|
| Travels to end of disk? | ✅ Yes (goes to cylinder 0 and 4,999) | ❌ No (stops at last request) |
| Head movement wasted? | Yes | **No** |
| Common name | "Elevator" | "Efficient Elevator" |

### Step-by-Step Operational Logic
1. Sort the request queue in **ascending order**: $R_{\text{sorted}} = [r_{(1)} \le r_{(2)} \le \dots \le r_{(n)}]$.
2. Find the split point $p$ such that $r_{(p)} \ge \text{initial\_head}$ and $r_{(p-1)} < \text{initial\_head}$.
3. Service requests from index $p$ to $n$ in ascending order (moving towards higher cylinders).
4. Reverse direction. Service requests from index $p-1$ down to $1$ (moving towards lower cylinders).
5. Sum the absolute differences for every move.

---

## 2.3 Algorithm 3 — C-SCAN (Circular SCAN)

### Operating Principle
C-SCAN is designed to provide a **more uniform wait time** than SCAN. The head moves in **one direction only** (e.g., towards higher cylinder numbers), servicing requests. When it reaches the **end of the disk (cylinder 4,999)**, it **jumps back to cylinder 0** without servicing any requests during the jump, and then resumes servicing in the same direction.

### The Wrap-Around Cost
The wrap-around from cylinder 4,999 to 0 is itself a head movement of **4,999 cylinders**, which must be added to the total.

### Step-by-Step Operational Logic
1. Sort the request queue in ascending order: $R_{\text{sorted}}$.
2. Find the split point $p$ as before.
3. Service requests from $p$ to $n$ in ascending order.
4. Move head from current position to **cylinder 4,999** (end of disk). Add this distance.
5. **Jump** from cylinder 4,999 to cylinder 0. Add 4,999.
6. Service requests from $1$ to $p-1$ in ascending order.
7. Sum all movements.

---

## 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| # | Concept | Formula / Rule | Unit / Range |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Cylinder index range** | $0 \le c \le 4999$ | cylinders |
| 2 | **Single-move distance** | $d_i = \vert H_{i+1} - H_i \vert$ | cylinders |
| 3 | **Total head movement** (any algorithm) | $D_{\text{total}} = \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} d_i$ | cylinders |
| 4 | **SSTF selection rule** | Pick $r_k$ minimising $\vert r_k - H_{\text{cur}} \vert$ | — |
| 5 | **LOOK sort + reverse** | Service $[p, n]$ then $[1, p-1]$ | — |
| 6 | **C-SCAN wrap cost** | $(4999 - H_{\text{last}}) + 4999$ | cylinders |
| 7 | **Worst-case complexity** | SSTF: $O(n^2)$, LOOK: $O(n \log n)$, C-SCAN: $O(n \log n)$ | — |
| 8 | **Number of requests** | Fixed at $n = 10$ (KTU spec) | requests |
| 9 | **Maximum possible movement (FCFS worst case)** | $4999 \times 10 = 49{,}990$ | cylinders |
| 10 | **Initial head position** | `argv[1]`, integer, $0 \le \text{head} \le 4999$ | cylinders |

> [!NOTE]
> Always use `\vert` or `\mid` in LaTeX — never the bare pipe `|` character — when typesetting absolute values inside markdown tables, or the table will break.

---

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

Disk scheduling algorithms are not merely academic exercises. They are deployed in:

- 🖥️ **HDD firmware** — drives use variants of LOOK/C-SCAN internally.
- 🗄️ **Database engines** (e.g., Oracle, PostgreSQL) — I/O schedulers choose request ordering.
- 📦 **Cloud storage systems** — magnetic and hybrid drives still benefit from these algorithms.
- 🚗 **Embedded/Automotive systems** — SSTF-like logic is used in real-time task scheduling.

The **SSTF** is conceptually similar to the **SJF (Shortest Job First)** CPU scheduler, **LOOK** mirrors the **Elevator** algorithm used in process scheduling, and **C-SCAN** is the **analogue of the Round Robin** policy for disks.
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

> [!NOTE]
> To enable deterministic, hand-verifiable traces, this section uses a **canonical KTU textbook example** (Galvin, *Operating System Concepts*, 10th Ed., Ch. 10) instead of random data. The same algorithm logic applies to the random data your program will generate.

## 3.1 Fixed Sample Input for Hand Derivation

| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| Disk range | 0 to 4,999 cylinders |
| Initial head position | **2,150** |
| Request queue (10 requests) | **2069, 1212, 2296, 2800, 544, 1618, 950, 1458, 1782, 1024** |

---

## 3.2 Derivation 1 — SSTF Total Head Movement

**Step 1.** Current head = 2150. Compute $|r_k - 2150|$ for all 10 requests.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\vert 2069 - 2150 \vert &= 81 \\
\vert 1212 - 2150 \vert &= 938 \\
\vert 2296 - 2150 \vert &= 146 \\
\vert 2800 - 2150 \vert &= 650 \\
\vert 544  - 2150 \vert &= 1606 \\
\vert 1618 - 2150 \vert &= 532 \\
\vert 950  - 2150 \vert &= 1200 \\
\vert 1458 - 2150 \vert &= 692 \\
\vert 1782 - 2150 \vert &= 368 \\
\vert 1024 - 2150 \vert &= 1126
\end{aligned}
$$

Minimum is **81** → service request **2069**. Add 81 to total.

**Step 2.** Current head = 2069. Recompute distances (excluding 2069).

$$
\begin{aligned}
\vert 1212 - 2069 \vert &= 857 \\
\vert 2296 - 2069 \vert &= 227 \quad \text{(minimum)} \\
\Rightarrow \text{Service } 2296, \text{ add } 227.
\end{aligned}
$$

**Step 3.** Current head = 2296. Minimum is $\vert 2800 - 2296 \vert = 504$. Service 2800.

**Step 4.** Current head = 2800. Minimum is $\vert 1782 - 2800 \vert = 1018$. Service 1782.

**Step 5.** Current head = 1782. Minimum is $\vert 1618 - 1782 \vert = 164$. Service 1618.

**Step 6.** Current head = 1618. Minimum is $\vert 1458 - 1618 \vert = 160$. Service 1458.

**Step 7.** Current head = 1458. Minimum is $\vert 1212 - 1458 \vert = 246$. Service 1212.

**Step 8.** Current head = 1212. Minimum is $\vert 1024 - 1212 \vert = 188$. Service 1024.

**Step 9.** Current head = 1024. Minimum is $\vert 950 - 1024 \vert = 74$. Service 950.

**Step 10.** Current head = 950. Only 544 remains. Service 544, distance = $\vert 544 - 950 \vert = 406$.

### SSTF Total

$$
\begin{aligned}
D_{\text{SSTF}} &= 81 + 227 + 504 + 1018 + 164 + 160 + 246 + 188 + 74 + 406 \\
&= 3{,}068 \text{ cylinders}
\end{aligned}
$$

### SSTF Service Sequence

$$
2150 \to 2069 \to 2296 \to 2800 \to 1782 \to 1618 \to 1458 \to 1212 \to 1024 \to 950 \to 544
$$

---

## 3.3 Derivation 2 — LOOK Total Head Movement

**Assumption**: Head moves towards **higher cylinder numbers first** (standard convention). The head does **not** travel to cylinder 4,999 — it stops at the **last request** in the ascending sweep.

**Step 1.** Sort requests ascendingly.

$$
R_{\text{sorted}} = [544,\ 950,\ 1024,\ 1212,\ 1458,\ 1618,\ 1782,\ 2069,\ 2296,\ 2800]
$$

**Step 2.** Locate split point $p$. The first element $\ge 2150$ is **2296** (at index 8, 0-indexed: 8). So requests at indices 8 and 9 are to the "right" of the head.

**Step 3 — Ascending sweep** (towards higher cylinders):

$$
\begin{aligned}
2150 \to 2296 &: \vert 2296 - 2150 \vert = 146 \\
2296 \to 2800 &: \vert 2800 - 2296 \vert = 504
\end{aligned}
$$

**Step 4 — Direction reversal. Descending sweep** (towards lower cylinders):

$$
\begin{aligned}
2800 \to 2069 &: 731 \\
2069 \to 1782 &: 287 \\
1782 \to 1618 &: 164 \\
1618 \to 1458 &: 160 \\
1458 \to 1212 &: 246 \\
1212 \to 1024 &: 188 \\
1024 \to 950  &: 74 \\
950  \to 544  &: 406
\end{aligned}
$$

### LOOK Total

$$
\begin{aligned}
D_{\text{LOOK}} &= 146 + 504 + 731 + 287 + 164 + 160 + 246 + 188 + 74 + 406 \\
&= 2{,}906 \text{ cylinders}
\end{aligned}
$$

### LOOK Service Sequence

$$
2150 \to 2296 \to 2800 \to 2069 \to 1782 \to 1618 \to 1458 \to 1212 \to 1024 \to 950 \to 544
$$

---

## 3.4 Derivation 3 — C-SCAN Total Head Movement

**Assumption**: Head moves towards **higher cylinder numbers first**, then wraps from 4,999 to 0, then continues ascending.

**Step 1.** Sort ascendingly (same as LOOK): $R_{\text{sorted}}$ as above. Split point $p = 8$ (same as LOOK).

**Step 2 — Ascending sweep**:

$$
\begin{aligned}
2150 \to 2296 &: 146 \\
2296 \to 2800 &: 504
\end{aligned}
$$

**Step 3 — Travel to end of disk**:

$$
2800 \to 4999 : \vert 4999 - 2800 \vert = 2{,}199
$$

**Step 4 — Wrap-around jump from end to start**:

$$
4999 \to 0 : \vert 0 - 4999 \vert = 4{,}999
$$

**Step 5 — Continue servicing from beginning**:

$$
\begin{aligned}
0 \to 544  &: 544 \\
544 \to 950 &: 406 \\
950 \to 1024 &: 74 \\
1024 \to 1212 &: 188 \\
1212 \to 1458 &: 246 \\
1458 \to 1618 &: 160 \\
1618 \to 1782 &: 164 \\
1782 \to 2069 &: 287
\end{aligned}
$$

### C-SCAN Total

$$
\begin{aligned}
D_{\text{C-SCAN}} &= 146 + 504 + 2{,}199 + 4{,}999 + 544 + 406 + 74 + 188 + 246 + 160 + 164 + 287 \\
&= 9{,}917 \text{ cylinders}
\end{aligned}
$$

### C-SCAN Service Sequence

$$
2150 \to 2296 \to 2800 \to 4999 \to 0 \to 544 \to 950 \to 1024 \to 1212 \to 1458 \to 1618 \to 1782 \to 2069
$$

---

## 3.5 Comparison Matrix

| Algorithm | Total Head Movement (cylinders) | Sweep Direction | Wraps Around? | Fairness | Starvation Possible? |
|---|---:|---|---|---|---|
| **SSTF** | **3,068** | Adaptive (nearest) | ❌ | Low | ✅ Yes |
| **LOOK** | **2,906** ⭐ | Bidirectional | ❌ | High | ❌ No |
| **C-SCAN** | **9,917** | Unidirectional (with jump) | ✅ Yes | Highest | ❌ No |

> [!TIP]
> For **this specific request set**, LOOK is the most efficient. However, the relative ranking changes for every different random request sequence — which is exactly why the KTU experiment requires you to **generate the requests randomly and report the results programmatically** rather than hardcoding.

---

## 3.6 Worked Numerical Verification

Let us verify the **SSTF total** by an alternative grouping:

$$
\begin{aligned}
D_{\text{SSTF}} &= (2150 - 2069) + (2296 - 2069) + (2800 - 2296) + (2800 - 1782) + (1782 - 1618) + (1618 - 1458) \\
&\quad + (1458 - 1212) + (1212 - 1024) + (1024 - 950) + (950 - 544) \\
&= 81 + 227 + 504 + 1018 + 164 + 160 + 246 + 188 + 74 + 406 \\
&= 3{,}068 \text{ cylinders} \quad \checkmark
\end{aligned}
$$

Verified.

---

## 3.7 Complete Reference C Program (KTU-Compliant)

```c
/* ============================================================
 *  KTU PCCSL407 - Operating Systems Lab
 *  Experiment 2 : Disk Scheduling Algorithms (SSTF, LOOK, C-SCAN)
 *  Disk: 5000 cylinders (0 - 4999) | 10 random requests
 *  Usage: ./a.out <initial_head_position>
 * ============================================================ */
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <time.h>

#define MAX_CYL  5000
#define N_REQ    10

/* ---------- Utility: sort ascending ---------- */
static int cmp(const void *a, const void *b) {
    int x = *(const int *)a, y = *(const int *)b;
    return (x > y) - (x < y);
}

/* ---------- SSTF ---------- */
int sstf(int req[], int n, int head) {
    int total = 0, cur = head, done[10] = {0};
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int best = -1, bestDist = MAX_CYL + 1;
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            if (!done[j]) {
                int d = abs(cur - req[j]);
                if (d < bestDist) { bestDist = d; best = j; }
            }
        }
        if (best == -1) break;
        total += bestDist;
        cur = req[best];
        done[best] = 1;
        printf("  SSTF step %2d : head -> %4d  (move = %4d)\n", i + 1, cur, bestDist);
    }
    return total;
}

/* ---------- LOOK ---------- */
int look(int req[], int n, int head) {
    int sorted[10], total = 0, cur = head;
    memcpy(sorted, req, n * sizeof(int));
    qsort(sorted, n, sizeof(int), cmp);

    int p = 0;
    while (p < n && sorted[p] < head) p++;

    printf("  LOOK  ascending sweep (head -> right):\n");
    for (int i = p; i < n; i++) {
        int d = abs(cur - sorted[i]);
        total += d; cur = sorted[i];
        printf("    -> %4d  (move = %4d)\n", cur, d);
    }
    printf("  LOOK  descending sweep (head -> left):\n");
    for (int i = p - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        int d = abs(cur - sorted[i]);
        total += d; cur = sorted[i];
        printf("    -> %4d  (move = %4d)\n", cur, d);
    }
    return total;
}

/* ---------- C-SCAN ---------- */
int cscan(int req[], int n, int head) {
    int sorted[10], total = 0, cur = head;
    memcpy(sorted, req, n * sizeof(int));
    qsort(sorted, n, sizeof(int), cmp);

    int p = 0;
    while (p < n && sorted[p] < head) p++;

    printf("  C-SCAN ascending sweep:\n");
    for (int i = p; i < n; i++) {
        int d = abs(cur - sorted[i]);
        total += d; cur = sorted[i];
        printf("    -> %4d  (move = %4d)\n", cur, d);
    }
    int dEnd = (MAX_CYL - 1) - cur;
    total += dEnd; cur = MAX_CYL - 1;
    printf("    -> 4999 (end of disk, move = %4d)\n", dEnd);
    int dJump = cur;                /* 4999 -> 0 */
    total += dJump; cur = 0;
    printf("    ->    0 (wrap-around jump, move = %4d)\n", dJump);

    printf("  C-SCAN second pass:\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < p; i++) {
        int d = abs(cur - sorted[i]);
        total += d; cur = sorted[i];
        printf("    -> %4d  (move = %4d)\n", cur, d);
    }
    return total;
}

/* ---------- main ---------- */
int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    if (argc != 2) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Usage: %s <initial_head_position 0..4999>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }
    int head = atoi(argv[1]);
    if (head < 0 || head >= MAX_CYL) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Head must be in [0, %d]\n", MAX_CYL - 1);
        return 1;
    }

    srand((unsigned)time(NULL));
    int req[N_REQ];
    printf("Initial head position : %d\n", head);
    printf("Disk range            : 0 - %d\n", MAX_CYL - 1);
    printf("Generated requests    : ");
    for (int i = 0; i < N_REQ; i++) {
        req[i] = rand() % MAX_CYL;
        printf("%d ", req[i]);
    }
    printf("\n\n");

    printf("======= SSTF =======\n");
    int s = sstf(req, N_REQ, head);
    printf("Total SSTF head movement  = %d\n\n", s);

    printf("======= LOOK =======\n");
    int l = look(req, N_REQ, head);
    printf("Total LOOK head movement  = %d\n\n", l);

    printf("======= C-SCAN =======\n");
    int c = cscan(req, N_REQ, head);
    printf("Total C-SCAN head movement= %d\n\n", c);

    return 0;
}
```

### Compilation & Run

```bash
gcc disk_schedule.c -o disk
./disk 2150
```

