## 📘 PART A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, Model Paper Style]**

### Question A.1 (3 Marks)
**"Differentiate between the SCAN and LOOK disk-scheduling algorithms. Which one is more efficient and why?"**

**Model Answer:**

| Aspect | SCAN | LOOK |
|---|---|---|
| Travel to disk end | Always travels to cylinder 0 / 4999 | Stops at the last request in current direction |
| Wasted head movement | Yes (over-scan at both ends) | **No** (no over-scan) |
| Head movement total | Higher | **Lower** (more efficient) |
| Implementation | Requires knowledge of disk boundary | Requires only knowledge of pending requests |

LOOK is **more efficient** than SCAN because it eliminates the unnecessary traversal to the physical end of the disk, which contributes to head movement without servicing any request.

> **[KTU University Exam – May 2024, Model Paper Style]**

### Question A.2 (3 Marks)
**"What is the 'starvation' problem in SSTF? Illustrate with a one-line scenario."**

**Model Answer:**
Starvation in SSTF occurs when a steady stream of requests near the current head position keeps being serviced, while a request far from the head **waits indefinitely**.

**Scenario:** If the head is at cylinder 2500 and a request for cylinder 2510 arrives just before a request for cylinder 100, the SSTF will keep servicing newly arriving requests near cylinder 2500 (e.g., 2515, 2520, 2505), and the request at cylinder 100 may never be serviced.

