### ✅ Model Solution — Choice A

#### Part (a) — LOOK Algorithm

**Step 1:** Sort requests ascendingly.

$$
R_{\text{sorted}} = [544,\ 950,\ 1024,\ 1212,\ 1458,\ 1618,\ 1782,\ 2069,\ 2296,\ 2800]
$$

**Step 2:** Identify split point. Since head = 2150, requests $\ge 2150$ are at indices 8 and 9.

**Step 3:** Trace the head movement:

| Step | From | To | Distance |
|---:|---:|---:|---:|
| 1 | 2150 | 2296 | 146 |
| 2 | 2296 | 2800 | 504 |
| 3 | 2800 | 2069 | 731 |
| 4 | 2069 | 1782 | 287 |
| 5 | 1782 | 1618 | 164 |
| 6 | 1618 | 1458 | 160 |
| 7 | 1458 | 1212 | 246 |
| 8 | 1212 | 1024 | 188 |
| 9 | 1024 | 950 | 74 |
| 10 | 950 | 544 | 406 |

**Step 4:** Total.

$$
D_{\text{LOOK}} = 146 + 504 + 731 + 287 + 164 + 160 + 246 + 188 + 74 + 406 = 2{,}906 \text{ cylinders}
$$

**Service sequence:** 2150 → 2296 → 2800 → 2069 → 1782 → 1618 → 1458 → 1212 → 1024 → 950 → 544

---

#### Part (b) — C-SCAN vs SCAN, and C-SCAN Computation

**Theoretical difference:**

| Aspect | SCAN | C-SCAN |
|---|---|---|
| At cylinder 4999 | Reverses direction, services requests on return journey | **Jumps** to cylinder 0, services requests in same (outward) direction |
| Requests near 0 after reaching 4999 | Serviced on return (causes higher wait for them) | Serviced **immediately** after the jump (uniform wait) |
| Total head movement | Lower | Higher (extra 4999 for the jump) |
| Suitability for real-time | Moderate | **High** (predictable wait time) |

**C-SCAN Trace:**

| Step | From | To | Distance |
|---:|---:|---:|---:|
| 1 | 2150 | 2296 | 146 |
| 2 | 2296 | 2800 | 504 |
| 3 | 2800 | 4999 | 2,199 |
| 4 | 4999 | 0 | 4,999 |
| 5 | 0 | 544 | 544 |
| 6 | 544 | 950 | 406 |
| 7 | 950 | 1024 | 74 |
| 8 | 1024 | 1212 | 188 |
| 9 | 1212 | 1458 | 246 |
| 10 | 1458 | 1618 | 160 |
| 11 | 1618 | 1782 | 164 |
| 12 | 1782 | 2069 | 287 |

**Total:**

$$
D_{\text{C-SCAN}} = 146 + 504 + 2{,}199 + 4{,}999 + 544 + 406 + 74 + 188 + 246 + 160 + 164 + 287 = 9{,}917 \text{ cylinders}
$$

**Why C-SCAN is preferred for real-time systems:** Even though the total head movement is much higher (9,917 vs 2,906 for LOOK), C-SCAN provides a **bounded and uniform waiting time** for all requests. In real-time systems, **predictability of latency** is more important than raw throughput. C-SCAN guarantees that the **maximum wait time** for any request is bounded by a single full sweep plus the wrap-around, which is a deterministic quantity — making it suitable for **hard real-time and multimedia** workloads.

