> [!WARNING]
> ### ⚠️ KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Mark-Deduction Pitfalls
>
> 1. **Forgetting the wrap-around cost in C-SCAN** (loss of 2–3 marks): Many students compute only the inner-sweep distances and forget to add the jump from 4,999 → 0, which is **4,999 cylinders** by itself.
> 2. **Using SCAN logic for LOOK** (loss of 3–4 marks): In LOOK, the head does **not** travel to cylinder 4,999 or cylinder 0. Adding a fictitious distance to the disk end is a common error.
> 3. **Forgetting the initial head position is the starting cylinder** (loss of 2 marks): The first distance is computed from `head` (argv[1]) to the first serviced request, not from cylinder 0.
> 4. **Choosing the wrong split point in LOOK/C-SCAN** (loss of 2–3 marks): The split point is the **first sorted request ≥ head**, not the median of the requests.
> 5. **Failing to handle command-line input validation** (loss of 1 mark in lab exam): Always check `argc == 2` and validate that `0 ≤ head ≤ 4999`.
> 6. **Confusing `\vert` with `|`** in LaTeX typesetting (loss of presentation marks in written exams): Always use `\vert x \vert` or `\mid x \mid` in LaTeX, never the bare pipe.
> 7. **Reporting total head movement in bytes or sectors** (loss of 1 mark): The unit is always **cylinders** traversed.

