## 5.X Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember ✨

- 🎯 **Disk range** is **0 to 4,999** (always). The number of cylinders is **5,000**.
- 🎯 **Request count** is fixed at **10** (KTU experiment spec).
- 🎯 **Initial head position** is supplied via **command-line argument** (`argv[1]`) — must be validated to lie in $[0, 4999]$.
- 🎯 **SSTF** = *nearest neighbour greedy* — risk of starvation, total movement is often the **lowest** in practice.
- 🎯 **LOOK** = *elevator algorithm that stops at last request* — no over-scan to disk end. **Best general-purpose choice** in this experiment.
- 🎯 **C-SCAN** = *circular one-way with wrap* — provides **uniform wait time**, always counts the 4,999-cylinder jump.
- 🎯 **Total head movement formula** (any algorithm):

$$
D_{\text{total}} = \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} \vert H_{i+1} - H_i \vert
$$

- 🎯 **Time complexity** of these algorithms:

$$
\begin{aligned}
T_{\text{SSTF}}   &= O(n^2) \quad \text{(brute-force nearest-neighbour search)} \\
T_{\text{LOOK}}   &= O(n \log n) \quad \text{(sorting dominates)} \\
T_{\text{C-SCAN}} &= O(n \log n) \quad \text{(sorting + linear sweep)}
\end{aligned}
$$

- 🎯 **Comparison anchor values** (for the Galvin textbook example, head = 2150, 10 given requests):
  - SSTF  = **3,068** cylinders
  - LOOK  = **2,906** cylinders ⭐ (best for this input)
  - C-SCAN = **9,917** cylinders (highest, but most predictable)

- 🎯 **Watch the unit**: the answer is always expressed in **cylinders**, never in milliseconds or sectors, unless the question specifies a seek-time function $T(n) = a + b \cdot n$.

- 🎯 **Watch the wrap**: in C-SCAN, the head goes **all the way to 4,999** (unlike LOOK), then **jumps to 0** (unlike SCAN which reverses). Both legs of the wrap are **counted in the total movement**.

- 🎯 **Viva tip**: if asked *"Why does SSTF sometimes give lower movement than LOOK?"* — answer: SSTF is a **greedy local optimiser**, so it can produce a shorter total path on certain request distributions, but it sacrifices **fairness and predictability**. LOOK is **globally optimal** in the sense that it never wastes movement at the disk ends.

- 🎯 **Viva tip**: if asked *"Which algorithm would you choose for a database server?"* — answer: **LOOK (or its variant FSCAN)** because it balances throughput and fairness without the massive wrap cost of C-SCAN. For **real-time / multimedia**: **C-SCAN** for predictable latency.

